and not being per\nmitted to leave mat city for twelve\nadditional hour. Tr.e Buick wvn solely\non its performance record.\nThere'\" no mor.- interested spectator\nto the final roundani the battle between\n\"Kid\" .Spring and Winter than Mr\nAverage Motoriet He's rooting hard for\nthe peppy Kid iu put the finishing\npunches over and to score a complete\nknockout. When the battle's won, be\nand th youngster will lock arms anO\ncelebrate with a prolonged Joy ride.\n(uy HarrU Huh-1. Compam\nThe Guy Harris Buick Company re\npert the following sales for the Week I\nending March 16:\nMlV Hett.e Morgan, city. 121 model\nuick Toujour.\nCharles Andern., city, 1921 moxlel 1\nf-pasfenger Buick.\nHugh West, city, 1921 model O-p.iss.\nenger Buick.\nWeJthelrner Daube ity, 1921 mod\nel 5-passcnger Buick.\nUcede-WIti Company\nThe Be.-de-Wttt 'ompany reiorts the\ntale ot a lxlge Brothers touring car\nto k. C McKiddy of this city and a\nIfc-ton Uodge Urotfhcr truck to Jor-dn-Knuckle.i\nIce Company of Wilson,\nrecently.\nWsiiiie irwin Malm Opan oni(,jon\n81 In Aid in Writing \"Nred of the Sun\nReaders who thought they knew Wat\nlac Irwln'e distinctively original atyie.\nnever suspected that Mr Irwin received\naki in writing \"detd of the dun.\" his\nlatest novel of California life and Japa\nn activities along the Pacific coast.\nAnd yet, in a letter written to the\nMaxwell Distributing Corporation. New\nTork Oty. Wallace Irwin makes the\nOpen confession thai If it had not be.-n\nfor the aid given hmi h Bella Donnn.\nJill fiery Maxwell uti-vd. he v..uld never\nhave been able to rather the matrnul\nfrom which Seed f the Sun,\" wa wnt\nM But we will let Mr. Irwin epi-ak for\nhimself in his own original wnv:\n\"In December. MM, I tnad myself a\npresent of a Maxwell touring car. 1\ndidn't ge her for pleasure, primarily,\nbut for busine. I had come to Cali\nfornia In search f material for a novel\non the .lapanrw-land problem; and If It\nhadn't been forthnt cieerfwl little Max\nWell, I'm no